<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="57" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="20" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1087,1112]" pageId="20" pageNumber="57">Etymology.</emphasis>
From a combination of Greek words “anthos” and “philia” (meaning “love of flowers”), referring to the flower-visiting habit of the new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="57" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="20" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1159,1184]" pageId="20" pageNumber="57">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles the foregoing two new species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Katoh &amp; Zhang &amp; Toda &amp; Zhang &amp; Gao, 2018" authorityName="Katoh &amp; Zhang &amp; Toda &amp; Zhang &amp; Gao" authorityYear="2018" box="[933,1070,1160,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Lordiphosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mikioides" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[933,1070,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="57">L. mikioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1076,1165,1159,1184]" pageId="20" pageNumber="57" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1076,1165,1159,1184]" pageId="20" pageNumber="57">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Katoh &amp; Zhang &amp; Toda &amp; Zhang &amp; Gao, 2018" authorityName="Katoh &amp; Zhang &amp; Toda &amp; Zhang &amp; Gao" authorityYear="2018" box="[1218,1334,1160,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Lordiphosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kimurai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1218,1334,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="57">L. kimurai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1340,1429,1159,1184]" pageId="20" pageNumber="57" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1340,1429,1159,1184]" pageId="20" pageNumber="57">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, in having the particular sex-combs, but can be clearly distinguished from them by the absence of anterior katepisternal seta and the shape of cercus, paramere, gonopods, and aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
